    {
      "id": "rKpvjN3h9RhkMatE",
      "questionNumber": 5,
      "questionText": "An ethar is more volatile than an alcohol having the same molecular formula. This is due to",
      "options": [
        "alcohols having resonance structures",
        "inter-molecular hydrogen bonding in ethers",
        "inter-molecular hydrogen bonding in alcohols",
        "dipole characters of ethers"
      ],
      "correctOption": 2,
      "correctAnswer": null,
      "questionType": "MCQ",
      "marks": 4,
      "negativeMarks": -1,
      "subject": "Chemistry",
      "topic": "properties-preparation-and-uses-of-ethers",
      "difficulty": "Easy",
      "solution": "Alcohol and ether are isomer with each other. So, with same molecular formula we can make ether  as well as alcohol. \n<br><br>For ex, \n<br><br>With molecular formula C<sub>2</sub>H<sub>6</sub>O \n<br><br>(1) $$\\,\\,\\,$$  alcohol will be CH<sub>3</sub>CH<sub>2</sub> OH\n<br><br>(2) $$\\,\\,\\,$$ ether will be CH<sub>3</sub> $$-$$ O $$-$$ CH<sub>3</sub> \n<br><br>In Alcohol there is hydrogen bond and in Ether there is Van der walls force of attraction. \n<br><br>We know that H bond is stronger bond than van der walls force of attraction as the atoms of alcohol are strongly attached with each other by hydrogen bonding so tendency of vaporization of alcohol is less compared to ether.\n<br><br>In alcohol inter-molecular hydrogen bonding look like this -\n<br><br><img class=\"question-image\" src=\"https://imagex.cdn.examgoal.net/hzWiFcmg3sGeMCPeN/GHZPl17wcQPhgE2NvhUdyz9hOQGNq/VIy3cXT94XVCecyegHr1TP/image.png\" loading=\"lazy\" alt=\"AIEEE 2003 Chemistry - Alcohols, Phenols and Ethers Question 184 English Explanation\">  ",
      "section": "A",
      "instruction": "",
      "examSource": "jee-main"
    },
    {
      "id": "m9e5ja21",
      "questionNumber": 6,
      "questionText": "<p>Given below are two statements :</p>\n<p><b>Statement I :</b> Dimethyl ether is completely soluble in water. However, diethyl ether is soluble in water to a very small extent.</p>\n<p><b>Statement II :</b> Sodium metal can be used to dry diethyl ether and not ethyl alcohol.</p>\n<p>In the light of given statements. choose the correct answer from the options given below</p>",
      "options": [
        "Statement I is false but Statement II are true\n",
        "Statement I is true but Statement II is false\n",
        "Both Statement I and Statement II are true\n",
        "Both Statement I and Statement II are False"
      ],
      "correctOption": 2,
      "correctAnswer": null,
      "questionType": "MCQ",
      "marks": 4,
      "negativeMarks": -1,
      "subject": "Chemistry",
      "topic": "properties-preparation-and-uses-of-ethers",
      "difficulty": "Easy",
      "solution": "<p>St-I - St-I is correct because both given ether are soluble in water $\\rightarrow$ Di ethyl ether and butan-1-ol are miscible to almost same extent i.e., 7.5 and 9 gm per 100 ml water due to H -bonding</p>\n<p>St-II : - St. II is also correct because sodium metal is not used with ethyl alcohol as $\\mathrm{H}_2$ gas release with ethyl a below</p>",
      "section": "A",
      "instruction": "",
      "examSource": "jee-main"
    },
    {
      "id": "m6srn6ae",
      "questionNumber": 7,
      "questionText": "<p>What amount of bromine will be required to convert 2 g of phenol into 2,4,6-tribromophenol? <br/><br/>(Given molar mass in $\\mathrm{g} \\mathrm{mol}^{-1}$ of $\\mathrm{C}, \\mathrm{H}, \\mathrm{O}, \\mathrm{Br}$ are $12,1,16,80$ respectively )</p>",
      "options": [
        "6.0 g",
        "10.22 g",
        "20.44 g",
        "4.0 g"
      ],
      "correctOption": 1,
      "correctAnswer": null,
      "questionType": "MCQ",
      "marks": 4,
      "negativeMarks": -1,
      "subject": "Chemistry",
      "topic": "properties-preparation-and-uses-of-phenols",
      "difficulty": "Easy",
      "solution": "<p><img src=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/fly/@width/image/jaoe38c1m7es42ny/54b158ed-02a3-42dc-bdf3-ce2a104d5a7e/d54119e0-f053-11ef-a864-2d89966ea2d7/file-jaoe38c1m7es42nz.png?format=png\" data-orsrc=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/image/jaoe38c1m7es42ny/54b158ed-02a3-42dc-bdf3-ce2a104d5a7e/d54119e0-f053-11ef-a864-2d89966ea2d7/file-jaoe38c1m7es42nz.png\" loading=\"lazy\" style=\"max-width:100%;height:auto;display:block;margin:0 auto;max-height:40vh;vertical-align:baseline\" alt=\"JEE Main 2025 (Online) 23rd January Morning Shift Chemistry - Alcohols, Phenols and Ethers Question 19 English Explanation\"></p>\n<p>$$\\begin{aligned}\n&amp; \\text { Moles of phenol }=\\frac{2}{94}=0.021 \\\\\n&amp; \\therefore \\text { Moles of bromine }=0.021 \\times 3=0.064 \\\\\n&amp; \\therefore \\text { Mass of bromine }=0.064 \\times 160=10.22 \\mathrm{~g}\n\\end{aligned}$$</p>",
      "section": "A",
      "instruction": "",
      "examSource": "jee-main"
    },
